## Verify Webhook Signature

### In a nutshell
Confirm that a webhook payload was sent by Vesicash and has not been tampered with in transit.

## How It Works

Vesicash signs the **raw request body** with HMAC-SHA256 using your webhook secret. The resulting hex digest is sent in the `x-vesicash-signature` header on every webhook request.

```@callout type="warning" title="Always verify before processing"
Never process a webhook event without verifying the signature. An unverified webhook could be spoofed by a malicious third party.
```

## Node.js Example

```@code title="Node.js / Express" language="javascript"
const crypto = require('crypto');

function verifyWebhook(rawBody, signature, secret) {
  const expected = crypto
    .createHmac('sha256', secret)
    .update(rawBody)
    .digest('hex');
  return crypto.timingSafeEqual(
    Buffer.from(expected),
    Buffer.from(signature)
  );
}

// Use express.raw() to preserve the raw body for signature verification
app.post('/webhooks/vesicash', express.raw({ type: '*/*' }), (req, res) => {
  const sig = req.headers['x-vesicash-signature'];
  if (!verifyWebhook(req.body, sig, process.env.WEBHOOK_SECRET)) {
    return res.status(400).send('Invalid signature');
  }
  const event = JSON.parse(req.body);
  // Process event asynchronously...
  res.json({ received: true });
});
```

## Python Example

```@code title="Python" language="python"
import hmac
import hashlib

def verify_webhook(raw_body: bytes, signature: str, secret: str) -> bool:
    expected = hmac.new(
        secret.encode(),
        raw_body,
        hashlib.sha256
    ).hexdigest()
    return hmac.compare_digest(expected, signature)
```

